Drupal core upgrade to latest version

✅ Description

Upgrade the Drupal core to the latest stable version for security, performance improvements, and compatibility with contributed modules.
Post-upgrade, all key site functionalities should continue to work without errors, including login, content editing, module integrations, and frontend UI.

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given the Drupal core is upgraded to the latest stable version,
When the application is deployed and basic functionalities are tested,
Then the site should function normally without errors or module conflicts, and no existing features should break after the upgrade.

Drupal contributed modules – Latest patches upgrade
---

✅ Description

Apply the latest security and stability patches for all Drupal contributed modules used in the project.
After applying the patches, verify that module functionalities continue to work as expected, and no existing pages, content types, or configurations are impacted.
---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given the latest patches are applied to all contributed modules,
When the application is deployed and core module functionalities are tested,
Then all modules should work without errors or conflicts, and no existing functionality should break after patching.

Update deployment scripts to add Support Data table to retention


---

✅ Description

The deployment scripts need to be updated so that the Support Data database table is included in the retention process.
This ensures that during deployments, environment refreshes, and cleanup operations, Support Data records are preserved and not wiped or lost.
After updating the scripts, validation should confirm that Support Data remains intact across deployments.


---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given the deployment script is updated to include the Support Data table in retention,
When a deployment or environment refresh is executed,
Then all existing records in the Support Data table should remain intact without deletion or loss.

Analyze way to retain the Client List Email Taxonomy


---

✅ Description

The Client List Email entries stored in taxonomy are getting removed or overwritten during environment refresh or deployment activities.
An analysis is required to identify a reliable method to retain this taxonomy data across all deployments and environment syncs.
The output of this analysis should include:

Possible technical approaches

Pros and cons of each

Recommended solution

Implementation effort estimate



---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given the Client List Email taxonomy is required to persist across deployments,
When an analysis is completed,
Then a recommended approach with pros/cons and effort estimate should be documented to ensure the taxonomy is retained without data loss.


Remove PHP 7.4 from Production server and update Supervisor config to PHP 8.2


---

✅ Description

PHP 7.4 is no longer required on the Production server after the upgrade to PHP 8.2.
The older PHP version must be removed to avoid conflicts and security risks.
Supervisor services that currently reference PHP 7.4 need to be reconfigured to use PHP 8.2 binaries.
Post-update, all application services should run successfully without interruption.


---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given PHP 7.4 has been removed and Supervisor is updated to use PHP 8.2,
When all services are restarted,
Then the application should run without errors, and no process should reference the old PHP 7.4 binary.


Update QV with Release 4.9 branch


---

✅ Description

The QV environment needs to be updated with the latest Release 4.9 branch to validate new code changes, configurations, and deployments before moving to higher environments.
This update includes syncing code, running deployment scripts, and ensuring all services come up successfully.


---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given the Release 4.9 branch is deployed to the QV environment,
When the deployment completes successfully,
Then the QV environment should run the Release 4.9 code without errors and all services should be up and functioning.

Prisma Alerts Remediation Phase 2 – Service Account Review


---

✅ Description

As part of Prisma security alerts remediation, Phase 2 focuses on auditing and reviewing all service accounts across environments.
The goal is to identify inactive, unnecessary, or overly privileged service accounts and update, disable, or remove them as needed.
This includes:

Reviewing service account usage and purpose

Validating permissions and scope

Marking unused accounts for removal

Updating roles for least-privilege access


A final summary report should be produced after the review.


---

✅ Acceptance Criteria (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)

Given Prisma alerts require service account cleanup,
When the Phase 2 review is completed,
Then a report of all service accounts with their status, permissions adjustments, and remediation actions should be documented and approved.


